  "text": "Eosinophil cationic protein is a granular protein that is released by the eosinophil ill vivo in the process of an allergic reaction and in vitro during clotting of the whole blood sample. Serum ECP might be useful as an indicator of allergic disease activity. The fact that the large majority of ECP measured in serum is in fact released during the dotting. process makes it necessary to thoroughly standardize the sample preparation. In the present study whole blood samples were allowed to dot for exactly 2 hours at 37 C. The reference range for serum ECP concentration using this procedure was 12991Ig/L. which is higher than that found in studies in which samples were allowed to clot at room temperature. [CITATION_1] .1I Clotting at 37\"C also gives better precision compared with clotting at room ternperature.! The influence of sample processing is greater in cases of eosinophilia.",
